"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nIntroduction&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSection One: ParticipationParticipation DataGender Gap&#xa0;Section Two: Which sports?Examples of sports popular with women and girlsSportOverall ParticipationFemale (%)MaleSwimming\n2,892,200\n1,870400 (65%)\n1,021,800 (35%)\nAthletics\n (which includes running)\n1,958,000\n823,000 (42%)\n1,135,000 (58%)\nTennis\n424,300\n192,900 (45%)\n231,400 (55%)\n&#xa0;\nBy comparison - examples of sports popular with menSportOverall ParticipationFemale (%)MaleFootball\n1,939,700\n119,900 (6%)\n1,819,800 (94%)\nCricket\n189,400\n12,900 (7%)\n176,500 (93%)\nRugby Union\n166,400\n10,900 (7%)\n155,500 (93%)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;Which women play sport the least? And which want to play more?Barriers and Motivationsa)&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPractical/lifestyle barriersb)&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPersonal/emotional barriersMotivations: What makes women want to play sport?Social: \n&#xa0;\nEmpowerment: \n&#xa0;Technical/delivery: \n&#xa0;Experiences: \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Using the insight &#xa0;\nSection Three: Investment in Women’s SportOverall Approacha)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThrough our investment in NGB Whole Sport Plans;\nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThrough \nmulti-sport projects aimed at particular groups of women and girls, for \nexample\n our Us Girls project with women under 25 in deprived areas;\nc)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTo create an environment where the norms of women’s experience of sport – \ni\ne\n that it is less usual, less expected and less catered for than men’s participation – are reversed through our B\nury project\n, I Will If You Will.\nWhole Sport Plan Funding:&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Should we add a specific target for women’s participation into WSPs?&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nActive Women &#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFace to face recruitment at public launch events \nwas\n really successful, particularly where women can meet coaches/leaders and other participants, and see example activity sessions in action.\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nE\nxisting participants\n were encouraged\n to bring their friend\ns and/or link with existing groups and organisations in the community so women \ncould\n \ntake part with people they kn\ne\nw and \nwere\n \ncomfortable with.\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nE\nasy-to-access practical information about what sessions will entail\n was important, as was \nr\neassuring women that other participants \nwould\n \nalso be beginners.\n&#xa0;\nKeeping women interested in sport\n&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMinimising potential practical barriers by offering: convenient session times, accessible venue locations, links to childcare facilities, flexible drop-in \nsessions and affordable prices.\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEncouraging and motivating women to take part – frequent contact from project staff (e.g. email updates, follow up contact with women who haven’t attended for a while), social atmosphere, fun and non-competitive sessions, fr\niendly and welcoming coaches/leaders and incentives (e.g. loyalty schemes).\n&#xa0;StreetGames – Us Girls&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Creating a place where more women play sport – the Bury pilot\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nRefurbishing \nBury’s\n tennis and netball courts, installing three outdo\nor gyms, modernising the changing rooms in the main leisure centres and starting work to install two mobile swimming pools.\n&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPutting in place an engaged and enthusiastic workforce that understands the barriers to women’s participation and motivation to\n ensure that activities are attractive to attractive, engaging and retentive\n              \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nReaching out to women through social networks and digital platforms to make sure they know the sporting opportunities available to them\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Investment in Facilities&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSatellite clubs&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWomen’s Sport and Fitness Foundation&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Section Four: Sport Governance&#xa0;\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSport England and UK Sport have set out a joint expectation within t\nhe 13-17 governance funding requirements that boards should be at least 25\n%\n women by 2017\n. \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nBoth bodies are jointly monitoring progress to this through \nour\n joint audit and assurance process. \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Women’s Sport and Fitness Foundation \nha\ns\n \nbeen commissioned t\no carry out \nan\n \nannual survey of women on boards\n. \n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSport England is also drawing together a pool of high calibre individuals \nwho \nhave expressed an interest in being on NGB boards, and we highlight advertised roles to those individuals\n. \n&#xa0;Section Five: Women and Coaching&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThese are available online and can be found here:\n&#xa0;\nhttp://www.sportscoachuk.org/resource/informal-female-participation\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;ConclusionSeptember 2013\n&#xa0;\nAppendix 1:Appendix 2:&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n"